		<div class="postbody">
			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple: You can have taxes or you can have jobs, but you can't have both
				</h2>
				

						
						
				<div class="content">
					<div id="post_message_1860624">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>PPatty</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1860607#post1860607" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">And people wonder why Brexit is happening. Even in the United States (which supposedly has a stronger central government), the federal government can't dictate state tax rates; yet somehow, the EU can set the tax rates of a supposedly sovereign nation and do so retroactively to boot.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>That is not what is happening here. The EU does not set tax rates. The EU is supposed to be one marked with free and fair conditions for the companies competing in the marked.<br />
The EU 'common marked' does not allow individual countries to subsidize companies to give them an unfair advantage in the marked. Irelands corporate tax rate is 12%. Ireland gave Apple permission to pay 0,005% instead of the 12% that all other companies in Ireland have to pay. Ireland is violating the rule about giving individual companies an unfair advantage.<br />
<br />
That EU members have been asked to pay back retroactively is not new. Denmark for instance have been asked to pay back a part of the farm subsidies that comes from the EU, because some Danish law was later judged to be like a government subsidy, and then giving farmers in Denmark and unfair advantage.<br />
<br />
<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Zarbonius</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">As an aside, I'm also not sure how any other EU countries were defrauded or deprived of potential taxes - as far as I can tell, *America* is the only other country that could claim to have been deprived of collecting these taxes (since Apple is an American company), not any other EU country. Are you referring to other European companies who may be doing the same thing as Apple?</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>Apple is not 1 company. Apple is more like a series of companies, where profit can be funnelled through a series of these countries to avoid paying taxes on profits. Like Apple funnelling profits to their Irish branch to pay the 0,005% in tax, instead of paying the individual tax rate of the countries where they made their profits.<br />
To be fair many international corporations do this, with many of them funnelling to Luxembourg or Switzerland and then off to Bermuda, Cayman Islands and the likes.<br />
<br />
Basically small or medium sized companies have to pay their fair share of taxes, while international corporations are allowed to use loopholes and secret taxdeals to pay next to nothing in tax to any country. Thats not only unfair competition against any other company that might help create some competition in the marked, its also depriving (actual) people of tax revenue, which means more of the tax burden in loaded unto them, because the biggest companies does not bear their fair share.
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
			</div>
			
			<div class="cleardiv"></div>
		</div>
	</div>
