			<div class="postrow">
				
				
				<h2 class="title icon icon0">
					Re: Apple: You can have taxes or you can have jobs, but you can't have both
				</h2>
				

						
						
							
						
				<div class="content ">
					<div id="post_message_1860626">
						<blockquote class="postcontent restore ">
							<div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>QuelianSpyralshot</strong>
					<a href="showthread.php?p=1860620#post1860620" rel="nofollow"><img class="inlineimg" src="images/buttons/viewpost-right.png" alt="View Post" /></a>
				</div>
				<div class="message">Technically - the EU is requiring the Irish to enforce the law as written, and stating that the massive exception given to apple was in violation of the EU treaty. Which does make sense.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div>The Lisbon treaty that established the current European Commission wasn't enacted until December 2007. Ireland's deals with Apple predate it; as previously noted in this thread, the commission itself has already said Ireland's deals with Apple were done legally. <br />
<br />
<font color="#333333"><div class="bbcode_container">
	<div class="bbcode_quote">
		<div class="quote_container">
			<div class="bbcode_quote_container"></div>
			
				<div class="bbcode_postedby">
					<img src="images/misc/quote_icon.png" alt="Quote" /> Originally Posted by <strong>Milton Finkelstein</strong>
					
				</div>
				<div class="message">The EU does not set tax rates.</div>
			
		</div>
	</div>
</div></font><font color="#333333"><br />
That's only on paper. In the way it interprets European competition law, the EC effectively claims authority over anything related to businesses. <br />
</font>
						</blockquote>
					</div>

					
				</div>
